D – Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
Definition

High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.

Depend on interfaces, not concrete classes.

Bad Example
class WiredKeyboard {

}

class Computer {

    WiredKeyboard keyboard = new WiredKeyboard();
}

Problem:

Computer depends directly on WiredKeyboard.

Cannot easily replace with WirelessKeyboard.

Good Example
Interface
interface Keyboard {

}
Implementations
class WiredKeyboard implements Keyboard {

}

class WirelessKeyboard implements Keyboard {

}
High-Level Module
class Computer {

    Keyboard keyboard;

    Computer(Keyboard keyboard) {
        this.keyboard = keyboard;
    }
}

Usage:

Keyboard k = new WirelessKeyboard();

Computer c = new Computer(k);

Computer doesn't care whether keyboard is wired or wireless.

Real-Life Example

Switch and bulb.

Switch should not depend on a specific bulb.

Any bulb can be connected.

Benefits

✔ Loose coupling

✔ Easier testing

✔ More flexible

✔ Supports Dependency Injection